{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7cfea61e-8c9d-48c2-911c-d29d09e7a6c3","content":"Here's what you'll encounter upgrading to .NET 10:\n\n**1. SslStream properties** — **Compile warnings** (`SYSLIB0058`)\n`KeyExchangeAlgorithm`, `CipherAlgorithm`, `HashAlgorithm`, and their `*Strength` counterparts are obsoleted. They already returned meaningless values for TLS 1.3. Use `SslStream.NegotiatedCipherSuite` instead.\n\n**2. SystemEvents.EventsThreadShutdown** — **Compile warning** (`SYSLIB0057`)\nObsoleted in .NET 10; the event was non-functional on .NET Core anyway. Remove the registration.\n\n**3. Queryable.MaxBy with IComparer** — **Compile error** (CS0121 ambiguity)\n.NET 10 adds new `MaxBy`/`MinBy` overloads to `Queryable`. If you had a custom extension method providing this, you'll get an ambiguous call error. Remove your extension or disambiguate explicitly.\n\n**4. XsltSettings.EnableScript = true** — **Compile warning** (`SYSLIB0059`) + **runtime break**\nXSLT embedded script execution is obsoleted and disabled by default. At runtime, transforms with script blocks throw `NotSupportedException`. To re-enable temporarily, set the AppContext switch `System.Xml.Xsl.AllowScriptExecution` to `true`, but plan to remove script dependencies.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:**\n\n| Feature | Impact | Diagnostic |\n|---------|--------|-----------|\n| SslStream cipher props | Warning (obsolete) | SYSLIB0058 |\n| EventsThreadShutdown | Warning (obsolete) | SYSLIB0057 |\n| Queryable.MaxBy | Error (ambiguity) | CS0121 |\n| XSLT EnableScript | Warning + runtime failure | SYSLIB0059 |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"94361ebf-c430-4135-91dd-49ec33857393","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about breaking changes and warnings when upgrading from .NET 9 to .NET 10. Let me address each of the four areas they mentioned:\n\n1. **SslStream.KeyExchangeAlgorithm, SslStream.CipherAlgorithm, SslStream.HashAlgorithm and their strength properties** - In .NET 10, these properties on SslStream have been obsoleted. They were already returning meaningless values for TLS 1.3 connections. The properties like `CipherAlgorithm`, `CipherStrength`, `HashAlgorithm`, `HashStrength`, `KeyExchangeAlgorithm`, `KeyExchangeStrength` are marked with `[Obsolete]` attributes, which means you'll get compiler warnings (or errors if warnings are treated as errors).\n\n\n2. **SystemEvents.EventsThreadShutdown** - The `EventsThreadShutdown` event in `Microsoft.Win32.SystemEvents` has been marked obsolete in .NET 10 since it wasn't actually functional in .NET Core and later versions anyway.\n3. **Queryable.MaxBy and MinBy overloads** - New overloads for `Queryable.MaxBy` and `MinBy` that accept an `IComparer<TSource>` parameter were added in .NET 10, which could potentially cause overload resolution ambiguities depending on your existing code. The issue is that .NET 10 added new `MaxBy`/`MinBy` overloads to `Queryable` with comparer parameters, so if the user had custom extension methods providing this same functionality in .NET 9, they'd now hit a compile error from ambiguous method resolution. There's also a breaking change with `XsltSettings.EnableScript` being obsoleted in .NET 10. `EventsThreadShutdown` is likely newly obsoleted in .NET 10 with `SYSLIB0057`. For `Queryable.MaxBy`, the new overload accepting an `IComparer` parameter could conflict with existing custom extension methods, causing an ambiguous call error. And `XsltSettings.EnableScript` is being obsoleted around `SYSLIB0059` as script execution in XSLT transforms gets disabled by default. I'll provide a comprehensive answer based on my knowledge of .NET 10 breaking changes.","outputTokens":1846,"requestId":"C421:200F2F:1EDA41E:22E0877:6A07D041"},"id":"40a71848-2528-4c8c-9aa4-fc8e3d478b7c","timestamp":"2026-05-16T02:03:11.610Z","parentId":"114f5afe-8276-4d61-9404-b50e0c17c462"}
